1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nc6 $5 {This move might look silly and bad, but
things aren't as simple at all!  Back in 2008, I played in the Russian league
where this line was introduced to me by IM Vladimir Kosyrev. I had suffered a
painful loss versus my countryman Ivanchuk and was supposed face Svidler with
the Black pieces next day. I was not in a good mood to prepare and repeat tons
of theory. Somehow, during our traditional team's meeting Vladimir convinced
me to play his pet line with 3...Nc6 in the French Defense. I also should
mention that this line was played by the 9th World Chess Champion Tigran
Petrosian, that's why it's caught my attention as well.} (3... h6 $6 {A weird
move. It looks like black neglecting principles of the development.
Nevertheless, some grandmasters used it as a surprise weapon! I remember back
in 2002 I represented the Ukrainian National Team at the Olympiad.  Just
before the round we had a walk from the hotel to the tournament hall. My
teammate V.Eingorn asked if he could play 3...h6. Somehow I thought it was
kind of a joke, but that's what he really did!} 4. Bd3 ({Black's idea is
revealed after} 4. Nf3 {as he can play} Nf6 5. e5 Ne4 {and now} 6. Nxe4 dxe4 7.
Ng5 {is not possible because g5 square is covered.}) 4... Nc6 5. Nf3 Nb4 {
I never studied this line. But during the game I decided that since white have
a huge lead in development, it's very logical to open position up.} 6. exd5 $5
({Eingorn's game continued} 6. Be2 Nf6 7. e5 Ne4 8. a3 Nxc3 9. bxc3 Nc6 {
The pawns structure reminds of the Winawer system but Black managed to keep
the f8-bishop, which is clearly useful.} 10. O-O ({Again it makes sense to
open position with} 10. c4 $5) 10... Na5 11. Qd3 Bd7 12. Ne1 c5 13. f4 Qc7 14.
g4 O-O-O 15. f5 Be7 16. Ng2 Bg5 17. Bf4 Nc6 18. Bg3 Qa5 {Black actually
obtained a very decent position, but unfortunately for my team later Black
collapsed as the position got complicated and we lost our match. 1-0 (56)
Gashimov,V -Eingorn,V Bled 2002}) 6... exd5 7. Bf4 Nxd3+ 8. Qxd3 c6 9. O-O-O {
I was very happy with my position as all of my pieces got developed, while
Black's ones are still on the last rank. Sometimes the simple logical play is
the best response when you are facing some rarely played lines.} Nf6 10. Ne5 ({
White has many attractive options:} 10. Rhe1+ Be7 (10... Be6 $2 11. Rxe6+ fxe6
12. Ne5 $18 {[%cal Gd3g6]}) 11. Qe2 Be6 12. Ne5 Qc8 (12... O-O 13. Nxf7 Rxf7
14. Qxe6 {winning a pawn}) 13. g4 O-O 14. g5 hxg5 15. Bxg5 $36) ({Or} 10. h3 $5
Be7 11. g4 {I think Black will be happy to return the pawn back on h7!}) 10...
Be7 11. f3 (11. h4 $5 O-O 12. g4 $40) 11... O-O 12. Kb1 Be6 13. g4 Nd7 14. Nxd7
(14. h4 $5 Bxh4 $140 15. Rdg1 Re8 16. Bxh6 gxh6 17. g5 Bxg5 18. f4 $40) 14...
Qxd7 15. h4 Rae8 16. Ne2 h5 17. gxh5 Bf5 18. Qd2 Bb4 19. Qxb4 Rxe2 20. Ka1 Bxc2
21. Rdg1 Kh7 $4 {a huge blunder, but Black's position was dangerous anyway.}
22. Qxf8 {1-0 Ponomariov,R -Legky,N Odessa 2005}) 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bd3 ({Fischer
already had a significant lead during the final Candidates match when he faced
this line.  That's probably why he decided to choose the safest option} 5. exd5
exd5 {This reminds a bit Petroff defence or Exchange variation of the French
defence.} 6. Bb5 {However, I feel that in symmetrical position it's kind of
more difficult for White to obtain something serious and I believe with
accurate play Black should be able to neutralize white's small initiative. For
example} Bb4 $5 {played by V.Kosyrev} (6... Bg4 $6 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Be7 9.
Bg5 a6 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. O-O O-O 12. Rfe1 h6 13. Bh4 Qd7 14. Re2 $16 {was
played at the famous match 1-0 (46) Fischer,R -Petrosian,T Buenos Aires 1971.
In this game, White achieved a very comfortable position rather fast.  I have
a feeling that many opponents of Fischer couldn't show their best due to the
enormous psychological pressure.}) 7. O-O O-O 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Ne5 {Now instead
of answering in a symmetrical manner, Black can try} c5 $5 (9... Bxc3 10. bxc3)
10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Bg5 Be6 12. Qf3 Re8 13. Rfe1 h6 14. Bh4 Bf8 15. Rad1 g5 16.
Bg3 Bg7 $132 {and thanks to the pair of bishops, Black seems to be doing fine.}
) 5... Bb4 ({I didn't like this move as after} 5... Nb4 6. Bg5 Be7 7. e5 Nd7 {
My general feeling was that Black was achieving an inferior version of the 3.
Nc3 Nf6 4.Bg5 Be7 5.e5 Nfd7 line.} 8. h4 $5 {I like this move played in the
spirit of the Alekhine-Chatard attack.} ({The young Caruana played} 8. Bxe7
Qxe7 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1 Nxd3 11. cxd3 $5 {an interesting strategical idea:
White don't mind having doubled pawns as he gets a semi-open c-file.} b6 12.
Nb5 (12. Rc1 Ba6) 12... a6 13. Qa4 Nb8 14. Nc3 a5 15. Ne2 Bd7 16. Qc2 c5 17.
Rac1 Na6 18. Qd2 Rfc8 19. Nf4 Nc7 20. Qe3 Nb5 21. Nh5 {and eventually White
confused his experienced opponent with some tactical tricks on the kingside. 
1-0 (43) Caruana,F - Hug,W Switzerland 2010}) 8... h6 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. a3 Nxd3+
11. Qxd3 Nb6 12. Ne2 {The knight can now go to h5 via f4, which is exactly
where Caruana re-rerouted it. White can also add a rook to the attack via h3
and g3. In the long run, Black has a slightly passive light-squared bishop
without any compensation for it.  Personally I would feel uncomfortable
playing such a position with the Black pieces}) 6. O-O $1 {I believe this is
the best move for White and one of the reasons why I didn't start playing 3...
Nc6 on a regular basis.} ({Caught by surprise, Svidler decided to sacrifice a
pawn after thinking a bunch.} 6. e5 Ne4 7. O-O {However, it looks like after
calm} Nxc3 8. bxc3 Bxc3 9. Rb1 h6 $1 {Black prevents all the possible
Ng5-related ideas and is doing just fine. White is ahead in development but he
cannot benefit from this factor as the position is closed.  Perhaps, it's fair
enough to say he doesn't even have a sufficient compensation for the missing
pawn.} 10. Be3 ({After} 10. Ba3 {I could play} a5 {preparing Bb4. So black can
castle short if he ever needs to.}) 10... Ne7 11. Rb3 Ba5 12. Bc1 Bd7 13. Ba3
Ba4 14. Rb2 Bb6 15. Qd2 a6 16. Bc5 Bb5 {1/2 Svidler,P -Ponomariov,R Dagomys
2008. After the game Kosyrev claimed Black was much better. He was clearly
unhappy I had not taken advantage of such a promising position and such a
lovely opening idea!  However, I was happy enough to solve quickly all my
opening problems with the Black pieces versus such a strong opponent.}) 6...
Bxc3 7. exd5 {An mportant intermezzo, as otherwise previous move for white
will not work.} exd5 ({It is too risky for Black to continue} 7... Nxd4 8. bxc3
Nxf3+ 9. Qxf3 Qxd5 10. Qg3 $36 {As now White will enjoy a very potent
initiative due to his unique dark-squared bishop.}) 8. bxc3 O-O 9. Bg5 {
Now position is not as symmetrical as it would have been after 5.ed ed and the
pin over the h4-d8 diagonal is clearly somewhat annoying. The play can
continue:} Bg4 10. h3 Bh5 11. Rb1 $5 b6 12. Rb5 a6 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Rb1 Qd6
15. g4 Bg6 16. Nh4 Rfe8 17. Qf3 Kg7 18. Kh1 Ne7 19. Rg1 $36 {maybe Black can
hold with some very precise play here, but it's not clear why he would want to
get a position like this!} *

