1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 b6 {I was inspired by a famous victory of
my compatrtiot V.Ivanchuk versus G.Kasparov when he crushed White exactly in
this line. You don't get to beat the World Champion with the Black pieces in a
very beautiful manner where the decisive move happens to be short castling all
that often, after all! The line doesn't enjoy much popularity at the moment.
Nevertheless, I decided to give it a try when I played FIDE Grand Swiss in
2019. My general feeling was that Black isn't risking to get mated rapidly due
to the closed nature of the position. At the same time, he doesn't need to
know as much theory as in the main lines - instead, the variation is all about
ideas and plans. However, Black's position looks rather passive and it's not
so clear what kind of compensation he gets in return for shortage of space.
What Black might count on is that White will get too excited/optimistic about
his chances. If that happens, Black gets a fair amount of counterchances. But,
if White is looking to play solid chess, it's pretty difficult to get
counterplay in this variation.} ({Playing 4...Qd7 is possible, but most likely
it just transposes.} 4... Qd7 {first. After} 5. a3 Bxc3+ ({or} 5... Bf8) 6.
bxc3 b6 {The game transposes to the lines that we study after 4...b6.}) 5. a3
$5 {I like this move a lot, as Black would prefer not to trade on c3 if
possible and now we are asking him to.} ({My game continued} 5. Qg4 {That is a
natural move that hits the g7-pawn. Unfortunately, the queen isn't placed that
well on g4 as it can get attacked rather easily and is misplaced, overall.} Bf8
6. f4 {Now the c1-bishop doesn't have that bright of a future anymore.} ({
I think this move also makes tons of sense} 6. Bg5 Qd7 7. f4 {with the idea to
continue with long castling, Bd3, Nf3 and so on.}) 6... Qd7 7. Qd1 $6 {I was
kind of happy to see this passive retreat which negates the Bf8-b4-f8 maneuver
and the time spent on it.} h5 8. Nf3 Nh6 9. Be3 Be7 10. a4 Nf5 11. Bf2 Ba6 {
Black managed to carry out all of his strategic ideas. The problem is that
White is still extremely solid! This should give you a fair idea of what I
think of this variation!} 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. Qe2 Nb4 14. a5 Rc8 ({Probably I
could have chosen to castle immediately} 14... O-O {But I was afraid of an
attack on the kingside, as I had weakened it with ...h7-h5. In fact though,
Black is safe.} 15. h3 c5 {Mountains of counterplay in the center are arriving
way too fast. White got no time for any kingside activity.} 16. g4 $140 Nxd4
17. Nxd4 cxd4 18. Bxd4 bxa5 19. gxh5 Nc6 20. Bf2 Rab8 21. Rg1 Rfc8 $17) 15.
axb6 axb6 16. Ra7 Nc6 ({It was possible to continue the game with} 16... O-O
17. O-O Ra8 18. Rfa1 {But white's position is still pretty solid.}) 17. Ra2 Nb4
18. Ra7 Nc6 19. Ra2 Nb4 20. Ra7 Nc6 21. Ra2 Nb4 {1/2 Christiansen,J
-Ponomariov,R Douglas 2019}) 5... Bf8 {This retreat looks a bit paradoxical as
Black just went ...Bb4. But that's exactly the way Ivanchuk played versus
Kasparov!  Interestingly, there is a relatively unknownn line 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5
3.e5 b6!? where Black does get some counterplay. Here White got two extra
tempi, but I am not sure what the knight is doing on c3!} ({A move in the
spirit of the Winaver would be} 5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 {However, as ...c7-c5
hasn't been played, Black is not applying any pressure on the White center. So,
White gets to do all he wishes!} Qd7 ({I had one game that featured} 6... Ne7
7. Qg4 Ng6 (7... Kf8 $6 {Black can avoid moving the kingside pawns, but then
he faces another set of problems. Namely, he would have a hard time getting
the rook in the game!  Generally, I have always found the idea to go ...Kf8 in
those Winaver systems rather suspicious.} 8. Nh3 Ba6 9. Bxa6 Nxa6 10. Nf4 $14)
(7... O-O) 8. h4 h5 {I decided to play the most natural move with white.} 9.
Qg3 ({In his book published in 2014, Negi had recommended} 9. Qd1 {but I was
not 100% convinced about the evaluation after such sample moves as} c5 10. Bb5+
Bd7 11. Bd3 Ba4 $13) ({Another tricky move for white can be} 9. Qf3 $5 Nxh4 ({
In the event of} 9... Ba6 10. Bxa6 Nxa6 11. Bg5 Qd7 12. a4 {White stops ...Qb5
and ...Qa4 and prepares Ne2-g3 to attack the h5-pawn. Black is in major
trouble!}) 10. Qh3 Nf5 11. g4 Ne7 12. Bg5 Qd7 13. gxh5 {and White enjoys some
annoying initiative on the kingside.} (13. Ne2 $143 Ba6 14. Nf4 Bxf1 15. Kxf1
Nbc6 16. Nxh5 O-O-O 17. Qf3 $13) {For example} 13... Ba6 14. Bxe7 $1 Qxe7 (
14... Bxf1 15. Qg4 $1 Qxe7 16. Qxg7) 15. Qg4 f5 16. exf6 Qxf6 17. Rh3 {But do
we really need to make things this complicated?}) 9... Ba6 10. Bxa6 Nxa6 11.
Qd3 Nb8 12. Bg5 Qd7 (12... Qc8 13. Ne2 Qa6 14. Qf3 Nd7 15. O-O $14 {1-0 (36)
Shirov,A (2726)-Kristjansson,S (2444) Izmir 2004 CBM 104 [Finkel,A]}) 13. a4 {
preventing Qa4} Nc6 14. Ne2 Na5 15. Qf3 {Finally I am ready to attack the
h5-pawn! This plan might sound caveman-ish but it is by no means easy to meet
it!} c5 ({Perhaps it would have been more stubborn to go} 15... Ne7 16. Nf4 g6
{But psychologically it's extremely difficult to weaken all the dark squares
out there.}) 16. Ng3 cxd4 17. cxd4 Qc6 18. O-O Rc8 19. Nxh5 Kf8 20. Qg4 (20.
Nxg7 $1 Kxg7 21. h5 {Would have been a much faster knock-out.}) 20... Qc4 21.
Rfe1 Nc6 22. Nxg7 $1 {After this much preparation, I have finally gone for the
kill.} Kxg7 23. Bf6+ Kg8 24. c3 Qxc3 25. Rac1 Qd3 26. h5 Rh6 27. Re3 Qf5 28.
Qxf5 exf5 29. hxg6 $18 {Due to the pin the c6-knight cannot be saved, so
calling it a day wasn't too premature a decision.}) 7. Qg4 f5 (7... f6) 8. Qg3
{We get an identical position after both 4...Qd7 and 4...b6.} Ba6 9. Bxa6 Nxa6
10. Ne2 O-O-O ({The old line is} 10... Nb8 {with the idea of bringing the
knight over to c4 via c6-a5. If that happened, Black would enjoy a firm
control over the light squares. However, such play is simply too slow. I
believe I've known the refutation since reading it in an old Soviet magazine.
Since then, nothing has changed!} 11. Nf4 Nc6 12. Nxe6 Qxe6 13. Qxg7 Qg6 14.
Qxh8 Qxg2 (14... O-O-O 15. O-O {black can't capture white's queen here.} h5 (
15... Re8 16. h4 Nd8 17. h5 Qf7 18. Bg5 Ne6 19. f4 Qxh5 20. Rf3 Qg6 21. Rh3 $18
) 16. Rd1 Rd7 17. Rd3 Rh7 18. Rg3 Qxg3 19. Qxh7 Qxc3 20. Qxg8+ Kb7 21. Bb2 $18
{Cruz-Vallejo,Los Barrios 1995}) 15. Rf1 O-O-O 16. Qxh7 Qe4+ 17. Be3 Qxc2 18.
Rc1 $18 {Gaprindashvili-Ranniku,Riga 1968}) (10... Kf7 11. Nf4) (10... Qf7) 11.
a4 Nb8 (11... Kb7 12. Nf4 $14) 12. a5 Nc6 13. axb6 cxb6 14. O-O {again black
requires too many extra moves to consolidate their position.} Kb7 15. Nf4 Ka8
16. Ba3 g6 (16... Na5 17. Bb4 Nc4 18. Nxe6 Qxe6 19. Qxg7 Ne7 20. Bxe7 $18) 17.
Rfb1 Na5 18. Qh4 g5 19. Qxg5 Rc8 20. Bc5 Rb8 21. Bd6 Re8 22. Rxa5 bxa5 23. Nd3
h6 24. Qg3 f4 25. Qxf4 {1-0 (25) Borisovsky,D (2304)-Stupak,K (2583) St
Petersburg 2018}) {It's really hard to say what to play for white, because
they have many good moves!} 6. Bb5+ {I was witnessed in 2017 in traditional
Biel tournament where I played myself how Morozevich crushed with this move
legendary veteran R. Vaganian. Since Morozevich played a lot French defence
himself maybe he knows better about small nuances.} ({White could also play} 6.
f4 {which would result in a position to the one from my game versus
Christiansen. Here, White would have a couple extra tempi. That doesn't look
too bad of a deal!}) ({Another natural move would be} 6. Nf3 Ne7 {[#] and now
Negi in his book recommended} 7. Bd3 ({The famous game that inspired me,
mentioned in the very first paragraph of the chapter, saw} 7. h4 h6 8. h5 {
But perhaps this space-grabbing plan didn't yield White that much.} a5 9. Bb5+
c6 10. Ba4 Nd7 11. Ne2 b5 12. Bb3 c5 13. c3 Nc6 {Obviously, the position is
now complicated, though White clearly didn't need to lose it. I would imagine
Kasparov's ambitions were an issue as he wasn't looking for anything less than
a win!} 14. O-O Qc7 15. Re1 c4 16. Bc2 Nb6 17. Bf4 Be7 18. Bg3 Rb8 19. Nh2 Qd8
20. Ng4 b4 21. axb4 axb4 22. cxb4 $6 (22. Nf4 b3 23. Bb1 {would have still
been complicated.}) 22... Nxb4 23. Bb1 Bd7 24. b3 Ra8 25. Rxa8 Qxa8 {Now Black
is dominating on the queenside. White, instead, doesn't have much play.} 26.
bxc4 Nxc4 27. Nc1 Ba4 28. Qe2 Qa7 29. Ne3 Qxd4 30. Nxc4 dxc4 31. Qf1 O-O {
0-1 Kasparov,G -Ivanchuk,V Horgen 1995}) 7... Ba6 8. Nb5 $5 {This position is
rather fresh.} {I saw that M.Marin recommended to improve on his game with} Nf5
$5 (8... Nc8 9. O-O (9. c4 $5 {actually was suggested by Negi in his book})
9... Qd7 10. Nc3 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 c5 12. Ne2 $14 {1-0 (49) Alekseev,E -Marin,M
Jerusalem 2015}) {But I kind of was not convinced due to the following
possible line} 9. a4 c6 10. g4 Nh6 11. Bxh6 gxh6 12. Nc3 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 {
all Black pieces are still on the last rank. At the same time, Black's
structure has been rather compromised as well. That's definitely not what he
wants to get!} c5 14. Ne2 Nc6 15. c3 h5 16. g5 Qc7 17. Nf4 O-O-O 18. Kf1 Be7
19. h4 Kb8 20. Rg1 {I think it's much more easier and pleasant to play with
the White pieces as Black needs to handle this extremely precisely to prove
compensation for his passive pieces and shattered structure.}) 6... c6 {
Ivanchuk handled the position exactly this way (though with the White pawn
already on h5).} ({After} 6... Bd7 7. Bd3 c5 8. Nf3 Nc6 9. O-O Nge7 {white can
start thinking of some concrete ideas after} (9... a6 10. b3 cxd4 11. Ne2 Qc7
12. Bf4 Nge7 13. Nexd4 Ng6 14. Bg3 Nxd4 15. Nxd4 Bc5 16. Nf3 b5 17. Ng5 {
1-0 (67) Fakhrutdinov,T (2499)-Ovchinnikov,V (2316) St Petersburg 2019} (17. b4
Be7 18. h4 $16)) 10. Bg5 $5 (10. Nb5 Ng6 11. Re1 Be7 $11 {looks almost equal})
10... Qb8 (10... a6 $2 11. Bxa6 $18 Rxa6 12. Nb5) (10... h6 $2 11. Nb5 $1 $18)
11. Nb5 Ng6 12. c4 {Now Black would need quite a lot in order to survive.
Perhaps if that's what he wants he should rather play the Poisoned Pawn
Najdorf or something!} a6 13. cxd5 axb5 14. dxc6 Bxc6 15. d5 exd5 16. Qc2 {
The position opened up which means the king is no longer safe on e8.} Qc7 17.
e6 Bd6 18. exf7+ Kxf7 19. h4 $1 Kg8 20. Rae1 Ne5 21. Nxe5 Bxe5 22. f4 Bd4+ 23.
Kh2 {The h8-rook isn't joining the game. A sample line can run} Re8 24. Rxe8+
Bxe8 25. Re1 Bf7 26. Re7 Qd6 27. Bxb5 h6 28. Rd7 Qxd7 29. Bxd7 hxg5 30. fxg5
Rxh4+ 31. Kg3 Re4 32. Bf5 Re3+ 33. Kf4 $16 {And there's not enough for the
queen.}) 7. Ba4 a5 (7... Ba6 8. Nce2 $14) ({As an improvement for black maybe
I can suggest} 7... Bd7 $5 8. Bb3 c5 9. Nce2 c4 10. Ba2 Nc6 {Now white will
need to spend some time to activate his bishop so Black might get some
counterplay.} 11. Nf3 (11. f4 f5) 11... Nge7 12. O-O b5 (12... h6 13. Ng3 $14)
(12... Ng6 13. c3 f6 14. Bb1 $14) 13. c3 a5 14. Bb1 h6 (14... b4 15. Ng5 h6 16.
Nh7 $14) 15. Nf4 b4 {trying to get the same kind of activity on the queenside
as Ivanchuk did in his game.} {Anyway,} 16. Nh5 {I still prefer White}) 8. Nce2
Ba6 9. c3 Bb5 (9... Ne7 10. Nf3) 10. Bc2 {White has a ton of extra space and
there's no compensation for that. The only question is how to increase our
pressure in the best way.} a4 11. h4 c5 12. Nf3 Qd7 13. h5 Nh6 $6 ({I don't
know why black didn't play} 13... h6 {At least it would have taken White time
to prepare the attack.}) 14. O-O Nc6 15. Re1 Bxe2 $4 {Looks like a suicide.}
16. Rxe2 c4 17. Bxa4 $18 {and black could already resign here} g6 18. Nh2 gxh5
19. Re3 Nf5 20. Rh3 h4 21. Bg5 Be7 22. Bxe7 Kxe7 23. Ng4 Kd8 24. Nf6 Qb7 25.
Bc2 Nce7 26. Qh5 Rf8 27. Nxh7 Kc7 28. Nxf8 Rxf8 29. a4 Kb8 30. Rb1 Qc8 31. b3
cxb3 32. Rxb3 Nxd4 33. Rxb6+ Ka7 34. Rb2 Nxc2 35. Rxc2 Nf5 36. Rb2 Qc7 37. Qe2
Rb8 38. Rxb8 Qxb8 39. Rd3 Qb3 40. Rd1 Qxc3 41. Qb5 Qc7 42. a5 Ne7 43. Rb1 {
1-0 Morozevich,A -Vaganian,R Biel 2017} *

