1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 c5 5. a3 Ba5 {This line was played by
Botvinnik in the World Championship match and later popularized by the
Armenian legends Vaganian and Lputian.  I used to think it was nearly refuted,
however as of late Black managed to come up with a bunch of fresh ideas that
brought a spark of life in this variation once again.} 6. b4 cxd4 7. Qg4 ({
During one important tournament, when Ukrainian team won World team
championship title for the first time in our history, I managed to score a
memorable victory in this line.} 7. Nb5 Bc7 8. f4 Bd7 9. Nxc7+ Qxc7 10. Bd3 a6
11. Nf3 Nh6 12. Bb2 Ba4 $6 ({Later Vaganian improved on his past play with an
interesting pawn sacrifice:} 12... Bb5 $5 13. Bxb5+ axb5 14. Nxd4 O-O 15. Nxb5
Qb6 16. Nd4 Rc8 17. g4 Rc4 18. O-O Nc6 19. c3 Rc8 $44 {1/2 (34) Bacrot,E
-Vaganian,R Moscow 2004}) 13. Bxd4 Bb5 {I guess this move - a waste of time! -
was one of the reasons why Black ended up in trouble} 14. O-O Nf5 15. Bf2 h5
16. Ng5 Bxd3 17. cxd3 Nc6 18. Rc1 Qd8 19. Re1 Rc8 20. Bc5 Ncd4 21. h3 b6 22.
Bxd4 Nxd4 23. Rxc8 Qxc8 24. Qa1 $1 Nf5 25. Rc1 Qd7 26. Qc3 {white took control
over the open c- file and slowly converted this advantage. 1-0 (57) Ponomariov,
R -Vaganian,R Yerevan 2001}) 7... Kf8 $5 {This is exactly the idea that made
me reconsider and study anew this variation.} ({As I was representing the team
of Ukraine during another Olympiad, we were facing the Armenian team and
managed to score an important win due to some rather deep preparation.} 7...
Ne7 8. bxa5 dxc3 9. Qxg7 Rg8 10. Qxh7 Nbc6 11. Nf3 Qc7 12. Bf4 Bd7 13. a6 O-O-O
14. Qd3 Rg4 15. axb7+ Kb8 16. g3 Ng6 17. Qxc3 {[#]} Nxf4 ({Some fresh games
were played in this line as well, however Black never got enough compensation
for the missing material.} 17... d4 18. Qc5 Be8 19. h3 Rd5 20. Qc4 Rxf4 21.
gxf4 Qa5+ 22. Nd2 $16 {1-0 (33) Bacrot,E -Vaganian,R Biel 2017}) 18. h3 $1 Nxh3
19. Rxh3 Nxe5 20. Qxc7+ Kxc7 21. Nxe5 Re4+ 22. Kd2 Rxe5 23. Bd3 $1 {Trying to
trap the Black rook in the very center of the board.} Rg5 (23... Kxb7 24. f4)
24. Rh7 Be8 25. Re1 {Rxe6 is a threat, so Black isn't on time to take the
b7-pawn.} e5 26. f4 exf4 27. Rh8 fxg3 28. Ba6 g2 29. Rhxe8 Rg8 30. Rxd8 Rxd8
31. Rg1 Rg8 32. Ke2 {I believe this is more or less how far our analysis
extended!} Kb6 33. Bd3 Kxb7 34. Kf3 Kb6 35. Rxg2 Rxg2 36. Kxg2 Ka5 37. Kf3 Ka4
38. Ke3 Kxa3 39. Kd4 Kb4 40. Kxd5 f5 41. c4 a5 42. c5 a4 43. c6 a3 44. Bc4 {
1-0 Volokitin,A -Lputian,S Calvia 2004}) 8. Nb5 Bb6 (8... Bc7 9. Qg3 Nc6 10. f4
a6 11. Nxc7 Qxc7 12. Bb2 Nge7 13. Bd3 Nf5 14. Qf2 Bd7 15. Nf3 Nce7 16. g4 $14 {
1-0 (29) Fedoseev,V (2724)-Mamedyarov,S (2809) Moscow 2018}) 9. Nf3 Nc6 10. Bb2
Nge7 (10... a5 11. Nbxd4 axb4 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. axb4 Rxa1+ 14. Bxa1 c5 15. bxc5
Bxc5 16. Bd3 Qa5+ 17. Ke2 $14 {1-0 (38) Dominguez Perez,L (2739)-Topalov,V 
(2740) Saint Louis 2019}) (10... f6 11. Nbxd4 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 fxe5 13. Nxe6+ Bxe6
14. Qxe6 Qf6 15. Qxf6+ gxf6 16. c4 $14 (16. f4 $1 $146)) 11. Nbxd4 {I think
this is the most convenient continuation for White as it's the easiest and the
most natural move. Black's core issue is the king on f8. Not only is the king
not comfortable there, but also the h8-rook is craving some opportunities.
Unfortunately, there aren't any.} h5 12. Qf4 Ng6 13. Nxc6 bxc6 ({Black also
tried simplifying the position. However, the absence of the queens doesn't
guarantee him an easy life, either.} 13... Nxf4 14. Nxd8 Bxd8 15. g3 Ng6 16.
Bd3 Bd7 17. a4 Ne7 {Black is definitely solid. But, while our advantage may
not be that large, it is very stable. We enjoy the extra space as well as the
d4-square. In a nutshell, White is pressing without any risk - what can be
better than that?} 18. b5 g6 19. O-O Kg7 ({This doesn't equalize, either} 19...
Rc8 20. Rfd1 Ba5 21. c4 dxc4 22. Bxc4 Rxc4 23. Rxd7 Rc7 24. Rxc7 Bxc7 25. Ba3
Ke8 26. Rc1 Nd5 27. h4 Kd7 28. Ng5 $14 {All White pieces are more active}) 20.
Rfd1 ({I think it would have been more resolute and justified to continue
actively.} 20. c4 {Now c4-c5 is about to squeeze Black, so he is more or less
forced to take.} dxc4 21. Bxc4 Bb6 22. Rfd1 Rhd8 23. Ng5 Rac8 24. Bd3 Nd5 25.
Ne4 {White is clearly having a much more enjoyable time at this point!}) 20...
Ba5 21. c4 Rhc8 22. Bf1 Kg8 23. Ba3 Nf5 24. cxd5 exd5 25. Rxd5 Be6 26. Rd3 Bc4
27. Rd7 Be6 28. Rd3 Bc4 29. Rd7 Be6 30. Rd3 {1/2 (30) Kulaots,K (2551)-Landa,K
(2616) Germany 2019}) 14. Qg3 $5 {This quiet move is my preference.} ({After} 
14. Qd2 a5 15. Bd3 Nh4 16. Nxh4 Qxh4 {Black gets to trade a couple more pieces.
Generally, we would rather keep as many as we can!}) 14... a5 15. Bd3 Ne7 16.
Qf4 Kg8 17. O-O Ba6 18. Bxa6 Rxa6 19. c4 {[%csl Rg8,Rh8] The h8-rook is not
particularly impressive. This factor determines White's solid comfortable
advantage. To make matters worse, the king isn't having a particularly good
time on g8 either.} Ng6 20. Qc1 h4 21. b5 (21. h3 $5 {looks more natural to me}
) 21... cxb5 22. cxd5 exd5 23. Rd1 Rh5 24. h3 Qd7 25. Qc2 Ra7 26. Qd2 Rc7 27.
Bd4 Bxd4 28. Qxd4 Ne7 29. Qb6 a4 30. Rac1 Rb7 31. Qa6 Ra7 32. Qd6 Rb7 33. Rc5
Qe8 34. Qa6 Qb8 35. Rdc1 Rh6 36. Qa5 Rhb6 37. Qb4 Rh6 38. Qg4 Re6 39. Ng5 Qxe5
40. Qxh4 {And White went on to win. 1-0 Naiditsch -Tregubov, IoM, 2018} *

[Event "?"]
