[White "Chaper 4"]
[Black "5...Bc3 6.bc Nc6"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C18"]
[Annotator "GM Ruslan Ponomariov"]
[PlyCount "113"]
[EventDate "2019.06.22"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Nc6 $5 {I was
introduced to this line by a Ukrainian GM Kruppa when both of us used to live
in Kiev. It is fairly similar to the variation 6...Qa5 7.Bd2 Qa4, and in fact,
there can be quite some transpositions from one variation to the other one. I
managed to achieve rather impressive results even versus super-GMs in this
line, which, I believe, is related to the psychological reasons as well: the
arising positions are quite original, not everyone feels comfortable in these
closed strucutres. However, I have lost much confidence regarding the
theoretical state of things after Volokitin prepared a very deep idea with the
White pieces.} 7. Qg4 {A very natural move that White should be generally
inclined to make, as now the g7-pawn is the main target he can try and
challenge.} ({Other moves are quite indecisive and give Black everything he is
looking to get.} 7. Nf3 Qa5 (7... Bd7 8. a4 ({Later I came to realize I wasn't
happy with this position on the Black side as the bishops are incredibly
powerful, so opening up the game favors White.} 8. dxc5 {two bishops favours
white to open position}) 8... Qa5 9. Qd2 f6 10. Rb1 O-O-O 11. Rb5 $2 Qxa4 12.
Be2 (12. Rxc5 a6 13. Bd3 b6 {and the rook is trapped!}) 12... c4 13. Rb1 Nge7
14. O-O Ng6 15. Bb2 Qa5 16. Ra1 Qc7 17. Ba3 fxe5 18. Ng5 exd4 19. f4 dxc3 20.
Qe3 e5 {Black was already winning just after 20 moves!: 0-1 (47) Svidler,P
-Ponomariov,R Lugo 2006}) 8. Bd2 c4 9. a4 Bd7 10. g3 O-O-O 11. h4 f5 12. Ng5
Rf8 13. h5 Nh6 14. Rh4 Nf7 15. Nxf7 {Here we agreed to a draw as White doesn't
have an active plan and has no way of making progress. Not a bad outcome with
the Black pieces in a KO tournament where all you often want is to hold!
Gashimov,V -Ponomariov,R Khanty Mansiysk 2009}) 7... g6 {Generally, the move ..
.g7-g6 is rather terrible provided the Black knight is already on e7, as then
all the dark squares get incredibly weak. Frankly speaking, I am not a huge
fan of this continuation here, either. However, in this position with the
knight still on g8 it is somewhat more justified as Black can try such ideas
as ...f7-f6 and ...f7-f5, which is exactly what Kruppa was showing to me.} (
7... Nge7 8. Qxg7 Rg8) 8. Nf3 Qa5 (8... Bd7 9. Qf4 ({Again, I think that this
favors White} 9. dxc5 {And the position opens up a ton.}) 9... f5 10. h4 (10.
dxc5 $1) 10... h6 11. Bd2 $2 c4 12. a4 Qa5 13. Be2 Nge7 14. O-O O-O-O 15. Rfb1
Rdg8 16. Rb5 Qd8 17. Qg3 Na5 18. Rbb1 Nec6 19. Re1 {Now only Black had the
right to play for a win as he can keep calmly improving his position, while
White didn't have any active plan whatsoever. 1/2-1/2 (85) Cheparinov,I
-Ponomariov,R Cuernavaca 2006}) 9. Bd2 Qa4 10. Be2 c4 (10... Bd7 11. O-O c4 12.
Qh4 $1 h6 ({If} 12... Qxc2 13. Bd1 Qb2 14. Ba4 Qb6 15. Rfb1 Qc7 16. Bc2 {
Black´s extra pawn wouldn't matter at all as all of his pieces are rather
terrible.  1-0 (38) Cleto,F -Lucio,J ICCF email 2011}) 13. Ra2 {will be a
transposition to the main line.}) 11. Ra2 Bd7 {[#]} 12. Qh4 $1 {[%cal Gh4d8]
This is a very concrete idea. If Black could manage to castle long, he would
have gotten a fairly decent position.} h6 13. O-O Nce7 ({This odd rook move
has been recently tried in some correspondence games!} 13... Rh7 $5 14. Rb1 ({
During the game I felt that the arising positions would be too unclear.} 14.
Bg5 Rg7 15. Bf6 g5 $1 16. Nxg5 Nxf6 $1 (16... hxg5 17. Qh8 Rg6 18. Bh5 $18) 17.
Qxh6 Rxg5 18. Qxg5 Ne4 19. Qg8+ Ke7 20. Qxa8 Nxc3 $13 {with a crazy position
where Black is fine.}) (14. Ng5 Rg7 15. Nh3 Nce7) 14... b6 15. h3 Nge7 16. Nh2
O-O-O 17. Qf4 {While things are clearly still complicated, Black's position
doesn't look particularly good as he didn't manage to push his f-pawn.}) (13...
b6 14. Bg5 Nce7 15. Rb1 $14 {1-0 (36) Sethuraman,S (2641)-Savchenko,B (2573)
Moscow 2020}) 14. Bg5 Bc6 15. g4 ({Even stronger would have been} 15. Rb1 Qa5
16. a4 Nc8 17. h3 Nb6 18. Rb4 Nxa4 19. Bf6 Nxf6 20. exf6 {as mentioned by Negi.
White would have gotten an improved version of the position he ended up
getting in the actual game.}) 15... Qa5 16. Rb1 Nc8 17. a4 Nb6 (17... b5 18.
Bf6 Nxf6 19. exf6 Nd6 20. Ne5 Bd7 21. Bf3 $36) 18. Rb4 Nxa4 {Black managed to
at least win a pawn.  However, it is not very important in such positions as
activity of pieces is the most crucial factor.} 19. Bf6 Nxf6 (19... Rh7 20. Ng5
Nxf6 21. exf6 Rh8 22. Nf3) 20. exf6 b5 21. Qg3 Qd8 22. Ne5 Qd6 23. f4 Nb6 24.
f5 g5 25. Rb1 {It's kind of unpleasant to be under such pressure. I was trying
to close the position down, but it didn't really work and eventually I ended
up collapsing in the time trouble.  That's a bummer, but Andrey Volokitin
showed a really deep prep versus this line, having basically buried it!} Bd7 $6
(25... a5) 26. fxe6 Qxe6 27. Re1 Kd8 28. Bf3 Qxf6 29. Rea1 Re8 30. Nxd7 Nxd7
31. Bxd5 Rc8 32. Rxa7 Re7 33. Bb7 Rb8 34. Bc6 $6 Qf4 (34... Qxc6 $1 35. Rxd7+
Qxd7 36. Qxb8+ Qc8 37. Qb6+ (37. Ra8 Qxb8 38. Rxb8+ Kd7 39. Kf2 Kc6) 37... Ke8
$14) 35. Qxf4 gxf4 36. Ra8 Re3 37. d5 Ke7 38. Rxb8 Nxb8 39. Bxb5 Kd6 (39...
Rxc3 $142 40. Ra8 Rxc2 41. Rxb8 Kd6 42. Rd8+ Kc7 43. Rh8 Kd6 44. Rxh6+ Kxd5 45.
Rf6) 40. Ra8 Kc7 41. d6+ Kb7 42. Ra4 Rxc3 43. Rb4 Nc6 44. d7 Nd8 45. Rxc4 Rxc4
46. Bxc4 Kc6 47. Kf2 Kd6 (47... Kxd7 48. Kf3 Ke7 49. Kxf4 Nc6 50. Bd5 $18) 48.
Kf3 Ke5 49. h4 f6 50. c3 Nc6 51. Bb5 Nd8 52. c4 Ne6 53. c5 Nd4+ 54. Kf2 Ne6 55.
c6 Kd6 56. Bc4 Nd8 57. Bd5 {1-0 Volokitin - Ponomariov, San Sebastian, 2012} *

