1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qa5 7. Bd2 Qa4 {
Black wants to block the entire queenside. After this move Qa4, it's
impossible for White to activate bishop with a3-a4 and Bc1-a3.  Unfortunately
for Black, his plan proves too slow.} {Nowadays I think more principle and
stronger is} 8. Qg4 {attacking the g7-pawn as soon as possible.} (8. Qb1 {
I decided to mentioned this rapid game not due to its incredible theoretical
importance, but rather because it is highly instructive in terms of showing
typical ideas and plans. I believe that it's crucial to focus exactly on those,
as once you grasp most ideas, it would become a lot easier to memorize
concrete sequences as well.} c4 9. h4 ({I have actually used this line myself
when I had to play the engine back in the day, as it was way weaker in such
closed positions as opposed to the dynamic ones.} 9. Nh3 f5 10. Be2 Nc6 11. O-O
b6 12. Bh5+ g6 13. Bf3 Bd7 14. Qc1 O-O-O 15. Ng5 Rf8 16. h4 h6 17. Nh3 Rf7 18.
g3 Rfh7 19. Bg2 Nge7 {Even now, at the moment of writing, my Stockfish claims
that White is slightly better here.  In fact, White doesn't have any active
plan. During the next 50 moves, I would just wait with relatively meaningless
moves like ...Kc7-c8, ...Bc8-d7, etc. Eventually, the engine desperately tried
avoiding the 50-move rule, opened the position up and created more weaknesses
for itself. 1/2 (153) Junior,(Comp) -Ponomariov,R Bilbao 2005}) ({Another
instructive idea was demonstrated by Kamsky} 9. Ne2 $5 Nc6 10. Ng3 Bd7 11. Be2
O-O-O 12. O-O Nge7 $6 {I think Black has no right to stay passive in such
positions, this is fundamentally wrong.} ({With the knight on g8 it's
interesting to look for counterplay with} 12... f6 $5 13. exf6 Nxf6) 13. Qb2 b6
14. Rae1 Rdf8 15. Nh5 Rhg8 16. Bg4 Kb7 17. Re3 $1 {nice idea} Nd8 18. Rg3 f5
19. exf6 gxf6 20. Qb4 Qxb4 21. cxb4 Ba4 22. c3 Bc2 23. Re1 f5 24. Bf3 Rxg3 25.
hxg3 Rg8 26. Nf6 Rg7 27. Bh5 Ng6 28. Bh6 Rf7 29. Bg5 Kc8 30. f3 Rb7 31. Kf2 Nf8
32. Nxd5 {1-0 Kamsky,G -Del Rio de Angelis,S Tegernsee 2019}) 9... Nc6 10. h5
h6 ({I think Black should try activating his pieces by means of looking for
active kingside play.} 10... Bd7 11. h6 Nxh6 12. Bxh6 gxh6 13. Qb2 (13. Rxh6
Qa5) 13... O-O-O 14. Rxh6 Qa5 {[%cal Gc6d4]} 15. Ne2 Rdg8 16. g3 Rg6 17. Rh4 f6
18. exf6 Rxf6 $13 {with chances for the both sides}) 11. g3 Nge7 ({And here} 
11... Bd7 12. Bh3 (12. Qxb7 Rb8 13. Qc7 Qxc2) 12... O-O-O 13. Ne2 f6 $5 {
makes more sense, looking for some counterplay before White manages to
consolidate his position.} 14. Nf4 fxe5 15. Nxe6 Bxe6 16. Bxe6+ Kb8 17. dxe5
Re8 18. Bxg8 Rhxg8 19. f4 g6 $132 {[%csl Re1]}) 12. Bg2 Bd7 13. Nh3 O-O-O 14.
O-O Kb8 15. Nf4 Nc8 16. Bh3 Nb6 17. Qc1 Ka8 18. Ng2 Qa5 {[#]} 19. a4 $1 {
White is giving up a pawn to activate his pieces and open up some files on the
queenside.} Nxa4 20. Ne3 b5 21. Bg2 {I like white's e3-knight as it's
supporting the upcoming pawn storm while also creating potential tactical
possibilities like Nxc4 or Nxd5. Since this position is already rather
uncomfortable, it makes me think I should have thought of an improvement on
move 12. Fortunately, though, my opponent went on to mishandle the position.}
Bc8 22. f4 g6 23. Bf3 a6 24. Kg2 Ne7 25. Ng4 Qc7 26. Rh1 Nf5 27. Nf6 Bb7 28.
Rh3 Nb6 29. g4 Ne7 30. Qh1 Nd7 31. hxg6 Nxg6 32. Nxd7 Qxd7 33. Kf2 Rdg8 34. Rh5
{I didn't want to let my opponent activate his pieces.  The h6-pawn isn't
going to run away or something, it's getting lost anyway.} (34. Rxh6 Rxh6 35.
Qxh6 Rh8) 34... Qd8 35. f5 $18 {1-0 (48) Ponomariov,R -Giaccio,A Villarrobledo
2007}) 8... Kf8 ({If} 8... g6 9. Nf3 Nc6 (9... b6 $6 10. c4 $14 {and White
gets to open position to his benefit.}) (9... c4 10. Be2 Nc6 11. O-O $14 {
1-0 (51) Sutovsky,E (2637)-Zifroni,D (2491) Israel 2015}) 10. Be2 {- this is
transposition to the chapter 4 with 6...Nc6.}) 9. h4 $5 {Again the most active
move for white. There is theoretical article about it in Yearbook 126.
Additionally, you can study the following game of Caruana as he went on to win
a rather nice one.} ({It is also possible to simply retreat with the same ideas
} 9. Qd1 {but it seems wiser to gain some extra space on the kingside, in the
first place.}) 9... Nc6 {Black is focusing his effort around the d4-pawn.
However, White shouldn't be afraid to simply sacrifice it, as Black's king is
rather suspicious and open files/ranks would favour only White.} ({It is safer
to try} 9... Ne7 10. h5 h6 {Now, White should try to improve on Caruana's play
by means of} 11. Rh3 $1 ({Black's position wasn't too bad in one of the recent
games that developed in the following way} 11. Qd1 b6 12. Nf3 Ba6 13. dxc5 Bxf1
14. Kxf1 bxc5 $13 {1/2 (28) Van Foreest,J -Vallejo Pons,F Douglas 2019}) 11...
Nbc6 12. Qf4 b6 (12... c4 13. Rf3 Nd8 14. Kd1 {Black managed to close a
position down but never came close to claiming any counterplay whatsoever.})
13. Rf3 Nd8 14. dxc5 Qxf4 (14... Qxc2 $6 15. Bd3 Qb2 16. Rb1 Qxa3 17. cxb6 axb6
{1-0 (41) Ju,W -Kashlinskaya,A Skolkovo 2019} 18. c4 $18) 15. Bxf4 bxc5 16. c4
{The queen trade did not resolve all of Black's issues as the f8-king and the
h8-rook as well as all the other passive pieces still aren't doing exactly
well.}) (9... h5 10. Qg5 Ne7 11. Bd3 b6 12. Rh3 Ba6 13. Rg3 g6 14. Rf3 Bxd3 15.
Rxf7+ Kxf7 16. Qf6+ Kg8 17. Qxe6+ Kf8 18. Qf6+ Kg8 19. Qxe7 Qd7 20. Qxd7 Nxd7
21. cxd3 $16) 10. h5 h6 11. Qd1 $5 {Now this is the right way to retreat
because Black was threatening Ne5} (11. Rh3 $6 Nxe5 12. Qf4 Nc6) 11... cxd4 $2
{According to Caruana, this is already a serious mistake.} ({But even after} 
11... b6 12. Nf3 Ba6 13. Bxa6 Qxa6 14. dxc5 $1 bxc5 15. Qe2 {White would enjoy
a pleasant position since Black has a hard time coordinating his pieces - in
particular, the rooks are the biggest issue.} c4 (15... Qxe2+ 16. Kxe2 Nge7 17.
Rab1) 16. O-O Nge7 17. a4 Kg8 18. Nh4 Kh7 19. f4 {and White is more active on
the both sides of the board.}) (11... Nge7 12. Nf3 b6 13. Rh4 $14 {1-0 (40)
Kulaots,K (2578)-Savchenko,B (2563) Budapest 2018}) 12. Nf3 dxc3 13. Bxc3 {
suddenly the Black queen is in danger because of an unexpected threat 14.Rh4!}
g5 14. hxg6 Qe4+ 15. Be2 Qxg6 16. Qd2 Nge7 17. Bd3 Qxg2 $2 18. Ke2 Qg4 19. Rh4
Qg7 20. Rg1 Ng6 21. Rf4 Nce7 22. Bb4 a5 23. Rxg6 {1-0 Caruana,F -Lenderman,A
Saint Louis 2018} *

