{[%evp 0,121,19,38,43,18,28,25,32,31,18,17,33,22,25,27,57,30,6,44,44,31,47,45,
15,22,63,40,40,43,59,63,55,30,37,26,47,35,42,28,51,24,31,30,35,35,30,29,30,32,
37,24,32,0,35,0,35,0,0,-3,3,-3,0,-14,-10,-13,1,-1,15,3,24,23,28,28,52,37,30,23,
30,25,30,31,54,51,54,51,36,-27,86,106,50,85,80,109,76,96,96,96,96,154,167,182,
182,204,218,215,273,253,155,99,197,349,374,244,236,201,299,315,353,315,425,464,
436,577] Let's look at this beautiful win delivered by Kamsky. The position is
very closed and seems to be rather drawish, yet he managed to trick his
opponent:} 32. Bd2 Bc6 33. Kh2 Kd7 34. Rh1 Rhh8 35. Kg1 Rh7 $6 {It's still not
entirely clear what White needs the rook on h1 for.} ({Knowing what happened
in the game it feels like suggesting keeping the king safe with} 35... Kc7 36.
Nf4 Bd7) 36. Nf4 Rf7 37. Bf3 Rh7 38. Ne2 Rgh8 39. Kf1 Rf7 40. Rgh3 Rhh7 41. Nf4
Rhg7 42. Be2 Rg8 43. g4 $1 {and suddenly White got an active plan. I can
clearly tell Black didn't particularly enjoy it!} g5 (43... fxg4 44. Bxg4 Nf5
45. Nxe6 $1 Kxe6 46. Bxh6 Qe8 47. Qf4 Kd7 48. h5 $18) 44. hxg5 hxg5 45. Nxe6 $1
