{[%evp 0,80,29,26,56,31,29,32,24,30,20,28,31,21,34,17,53,42,73,81,83,94,79,96,
96,77,85,75,68,-11,36,-29,-17,-19,-28,-23,-4,-32,-48,-46,-46,-51,-50,-60,-64,
-71,-72,-88,-87,-85,-124,-130,-130,-130,-97,-136,-136,-128,-145,-143,-146,-123,
-126,-134,-134,-134,-132,-132,-132,-132,-154,-169,-167,-171,-175,-167,-170,
-171,-167,-174,-174,-175,-208]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 c5 5. a3
Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qc7 {This is the favorite line of Predrag Nikolic. Black wants
to defend the g7-pawn by moving his f-pawn up and protecting the g7-pawn with
the queen.} 7. Qg4 {The most popular and logical move for White.} ({Before
going ahead and seeing what happens in the main line, I'd like to suggest an
interesting alternative for White} 7. h4 $5 {Probably black should play} Ne7 {
Other moves don't look very promising:} (7... Nc6 8. h5 h6 9. Nf3 {White gains
lots of space on the kingside. One boon of having a pawn advanced all the way
up to h5 is that Black's knight can never make it to g6, meaning that Black
cannot add another attacker and challenge the e5-pawn.}) (7... cxd4 8. cxd4
Qc3+ 9. Bd2 Qxd4 10. Nf3 Qe4+ 11. Be3 Ne7 12. Bd3 Qg4 13. Rh3 $44 {Black wins
a pawn but he won't enjoy it greatly as the White pieces are incredibly active
and the queen on g4 is rather vulnerable.}) ({Too slow is} 7... b6 {intending
to exchange the light-squared bishops.} 8. h5 h6 (8... Ba6 9. Bxa6 Nxa6 10. Qd3
Nb8 11. Qg3 f5 (11... Kf8 12. h6 $16) 12. Ne2 Nc6 13. Nf4 Nd8 (13... Kf7 14.
