Nxe5 24. Rc7+ Kxd6 25. Bb4+ Kd5 26. Rd1+ Ke4 27. f3+ Kf5 {[#]} 28. Bxe7 ({
Now the somewhat paradoxical} 28. g4+ Kf4 29. Bd6 $3 {was winning for white}
Nd5 $140 30. Kf2) 28... Rhc8 29. g4+ Kf4 30. Bd6 Rxc7 31. Bxc7 Rc8 32. Rd7 Ke3
33. Bxe5 Rc1+ 34. Rd1 Rxd1+ 35. Kxd1 Kxf3 36. Bxg7 Kxg4 37. Bxh6 Kxh5 {and
Black managed to save a draw as White got a "wrong" bishop} 38. Bf4 Kg4 39. Bb8
Kf5 40. Bxa7 Ke4 41. Bxb6 {1/2 Dominguez Perez,L -So,W Saint Louis 2017}) ({
Few weeks later during one of Magnus's online tournaments Ian tried a couple
new lines} 10... cxd4 $5 {in the spirit of the poisoned pawn variation. It's
difficult to say though if Ian thought it was a serious move or bluff as
people tend to take more risks in online chess.} 11. Qxg7 Rg8 12. Qxh6 Qxe5+ {
Caruana played very naturally} 13. Ne2 ({However, there were some tricks at
White's disposal} 13. Kd1 $5 dxc3 (13... Nf5 $6 14. Nf3 Qe4 15. Qf4 dxc3 16. h6
Rh8 17. Qc7 Bd7 18. Bg5 $18 {1-0 (46) Motylev,A -Studer,N Tallinn 2019}) 14.
Nf3 Qh8 15. Qxh8 Rxh8 16. Bg5 $5 (16. Rb3 f6 17. Rxc3 e5) (16. Nd4 Kf8 (16...
Ba6 17. Nb5 Bxb5 18. Bxb5+ Kf8 19. Rh3 $14) 17. Nb5 Nbc6 18. Bg5 e5 19. h6 Bf5
20. Nxc3 d4 $13) 16... Ng8 17. h6 f6 18. h7 fxg5 19. hxg8=Q+ Rxg8 20. Rh7 $44 {
Even after the queen trade, White would still enjoy a clear initiative.}) 13...
dxc3 14. Qf4 ({Again, other ideas were possible as well} 14. f3 $5 Qc7 (14...
d4 $6 15. Bf4 Qc5 16. Ng3 Bb7 17. Rb5 $1 Qxa3 18. Rg5 {and White's h-passer is
very dangerous} Nd7 (18... Rf8 19. Qxf8+ $3 Kxf8 20. h6) 19. Rxg8+ Nxg8 20. Qg7
O-O-O 21. Kf2 $16 e5 22. Bxe5 Nxe5 23. Qxe5) 15. Qf6 (15. Qe3 Ba6 16. h6 Nd7
17. h7 Rh8) 15... Ba6 16. Bf4 Qc5 {looks like Black is holding, but he's
walking a very thin line}) 14... Qxf4 15. Bxf4 Nbc6 (15... Ba6 $5) 16. Nxc3 e5
17. Bd2 (17. Nb5 $5 exf4 $140 18. Nc7+ Kd7 19. Nxa8 Bb7 20. Nxb6+ axb6 21. Rxb6
Kc7 22. Rb3) 17... Bf5 18. f3 Rd8 19. Kf2 f6 $13 {In this endgame, both sides
could play for a win. 1/2 (69) Caruana,F -Nepomniachtchi,I chess24.com INT 2020
}) 11. Bb5+ Kf8 {In the hindsight, we know Black had a hard time coordinating
his rooks later on. So, maybe he had to handle this differently.} ({I don't
know how stupid was an idea with} 11... Kd8 $5 {since the rook protects the
kingside pawns.} {So far I couldn't find a direct refutation of such play.} 12.
Bd3 (12. Qf4 Bd7 (12... c4 $2 13. Qxf7 a6 14. Be8 Rxe8 15. Qxg7 $16) 13. Bd3 c4
14. Bf1 Rf8 15. Qg4 Rg8 16. Qf3 Rf8 17. Ne2 Ba4 18. Nf4 Qc6 19. Rb2 Na6 20. g3
Kc7 21. Bh3 Kb7 22. O-O Nc7 {this is a typical closed position. Black doesn't
have any active ideas, however it's not easy for White to do much, either.})
12... cxd4 ({Complications favour White} 12... Ba6 13. Bh7 $1 {that's a crazy
position[#]} cxd4 14. Bxg8 Qxc3+ 15. Bd2 Qxc2 (15... Qc4 16. Ne2 Nbc6 17. Bxf7
Nxe5 18. Rb4 $1) 16. Rc1 Qd3 17. Ne2 Nxg8 18. Bb4) 13. cxd4 (13. Nf3 $5 Ba6 14.
Bh7 Nd7 15. Bxg8 Qxc3+ 16. Bd2 Qxc2 17. Rc1 Qd3 18. Nxd4 Nxg8 19. Rd1 $13)
13... Ba6 14. Qd1 Bxd3 (14... Qc3+ 15. Bd2 Qxd4 16. Nf3 Qa4 17. Rh4 Qd7 {
looks very dangerous for Black, but there is no clear refutation or punishment}
18. c4 dxc4 19. Bxc4 Bxc4 20. Rxc4 Na6 21. Rd4 Nd5 22. Kf1 Nc5 23. Kg1 $44) 15.
Qxd3 Nbc6 16. Bd2 f6 $132 {We need more practical tests to better understand
what the hell is actually going on!}) 12. Bd3 Ba6 13. dxc5 $1 {MVL clearly
prepared deeply as well, as his next move was played very fast, even though to
me it seemed very unnatural.} ({I can only guess that Ian was ready to meet} 
13. Bd2 Bxd3 14. cxd3 cxd4 15. cxd4 Qc2 16. Rc1 {and now the whole thing makes
sense} Qb2 $5 17. Nf3 Nbc6 18. Ke2 Ke8 {[%cal Ge8d7] with a rook on g8 Black's
king can walk in the center and the rooks get connected quite easily.}) 13...
Bxd3 (13... bxc5 14. Nf3 c4 15. Be2 Nbc6 16. Qf4 {Actually, now the rook on g8
is a problem for...Black! The reason is that the king wants to go to h7 via g8
but it can't.} Qa5 17. Bd2 Rh8 18. O-O Kg8 19. a4 $5 {black's position looks
very passive}) 14. cxd3 Nd7 {Both players were still making their moves very
fast.} 15. d4 bxc5 16. Qd1 $1 {and only after this move Nepomniatchi started
thinking.} ({It's interesting that later in their online encounter MVL played} 
16. Ne2 {I like this move less.  However, besides objective merits, there are
also psychological reasons, such as avoiding the opponent's home prep, maybe
that's why it was played.} Rb8 17. Rxb8+ Qxb8 18. O-O c4 19. Rd1 Qb1 $6 ({
Black should have played} 19... Qb3 20. Rd2 Nb6 21. Rb2 Qd1+ 22. Kh2 Ke8 {
and things would have been very unclear as White is lacking coordination.}) 20.
Rd2 Nb6 21. Rb2 Qd3 22. Bd2 Ke8 23. Nf4 $16 {Again, White was the one to win
the theoretical battle. But...not the game - the tricky Nepo managed to escape
and save half a point!  1/2 (62) Vachier-Lagrave,M -Nepomniachtchi,I chess24.
com INT 2020}) 16... Qa5 ({A similar position would arise after} 16... Rb8 17.
Rxb8+ Qxb8 18. Ne2 Qb5 19. O-O Qc4 20. dxc5 Nxc5 21. Nd4 {White isn't winning
by force, but the king on f8 is a long-term issue.}) 17. Bd2 Rb8 ({Apparently,
we would be happy to offer a pawn} 17... Qxa3 18. Ne2 Qa6 19. O-O {as with the
king on f8, opening the position up looks like a suicide for Black.}) 18. Ne2
c4 $6 {This move was criticized a lot in the post-mortem. The desire to close
things down is understandable, however now Black won't have any counterplay
whatsoever.} (18... Ke8 19. O-O Kd8 20. c4 {Doesn't look good for Black, either
}) ({At the same time, it's hard to say how Black should defend.} 18... Rxb1
19. Qxb1 Qa6 20. a4 $1 Nc6 (20... Qxa4 21. O-O) 21. Qb5 Qxb5 22. axb5 Na5 23.
O-O $1 (23. dxc5 Nxc5 24. Be3 Nd3+ 25. Kd1 Nxe5) 23... Nb3 (23... Nc4 24. Ra1
$1 {Again, the f8-king and the g8-rook cause Black trouble.} Nxd2 25. Rxa7 Ke7
26. dxc5) 24. Be3 c4 25. f4 Ke7 26. f5 exf5 (26... Rb8 27. Nf4) 27. Rxf5 Rb8
28. Rf3 Rxb5 29. Ng3 Rb6 30. Nf5+ Kf8 31. Rg3 {and even without queens the
position is very difficult for Black!}) 19. O-O Rb6 20. Qc2 Rh8 21. a4 Ke8 {[#]
} 22. Rb4 $5 {A very pretty exchange sacrifice.} ({However, even the simple} 
22. g4 {would have made Black's position very difficult}) 22... Nc6 ({It would
have been more stubborn to try} 22... Nb8 23. g4 Nbc6 24. Rxb6 axb6 25. f4 f5
26. exf6 gxf6 27. f5 e5 28. Kg2 {but again, the position would have been very
difficult for Black as there are too many weaknesses.}) 23. f4 Ne7 {A sad need.
} ({But in the event of} 23... Nxb4 24. cxb4 Qa6 25. f5 {White's attack is
developing very smoothly}) 24. Rfb1 f5 25. Rb5 Qa6 26. Bc1 {[%cal Gc1a3]} Kf7
27. Ba3 Rhb8 28. Bxe7 Kxe7 29. g4 Rxb5 30. axb5 Rxb5 31. gxf5 Rxb1+ 32. Qxb1
exf5 33. Ng3 Qb6 34. Nxf5+ Kf8 35. Qa1 Qe6 36. Ng3 Qg4 37. Kg2 Qxf4 38. Qxa7
Ke7 39. Qa3+ Kd8 40. Qd6 g5 41. hxg6 h5 42. g7 {1-0 Vachier Lagrave,M
-Nepomniachtchi,I Ekaterinburg 2020} *

