{[%evp 0,85,19,38,43,18,28,25,16,32,26,18,29,29,15,25,48,-4,27,-11,23,24,29,-2,
22,28,27,17,19,22,23,11,11,3,3,-45,-13,-45,-46,31,0,0,48,-2,5,90,119,86,86,68,
49,63,63,76,76,76,67,67,87,100,156,138,86,71,69,74,81,101,104,108,108,129,129,
126,154,147,175,191,191,194,194,212,227,227,244,214,259,274]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5
3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 Ne7 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c5 7. Qg4 ({Right now I like the
following idea better} 7. h4 $5 {but let's take a look at other options, as
many variations are highly transpositional.}) 7... Kf8 {As I had explained
earlier, I am not the biggest fan of the ideas with ...Kf8 as Black gets two
problems to resolve - both his king and his h8-rook aren't great.  However,
White has to play precisely as well as otherwise his weaknesses will tell. [#]}
8. h4 $5 {We are making this move nevertheless. The point is that it's crucial
to look for active play on the kingside as opposed to simply castling short.
That is exactly why h4 is so useful: it enables the rook lift via h3.} ({
I have quite bad memories about this line, as it occured in an important team
match between Ukraine and USA back at the Olympiad of 2008 when Ivanchuk lost
in less than two hours on board 1!} 8. Bd2 $5 Qc7 {Since the c3-square has
been already defended, this move doesn't make much sense to me.} ({It makes
more sense to start with} 8... b6 {but white can play in a similar manner} 9.
Bd3 Ba6 10. dxc5 bxc5 11. Bxa6 Nxa6 12. c4 $1 {Since the king is stuck on f8,
the idea of opening the position up cannot be bad!}) 9. Bd3 b6 10. Nf3 Ba6 11.
dxc5 $5 {A typical pattern - we are opening things up for our bishop pair.}
Qxc5 12. O-O Bxd3 13. cxd3 Nbc6 14. a4 {It's really difficult for Black to
finish his development.} h5 15. Qg5 Nf5 16. Rfb1 Kg8 17. Rb5 Qe7 18. Qf4 {
[%csl Rh8]} Qd7 19. Rab1 Rc8 20. h3 Rh6 21. a5 bxa5 22. Qa4 Rg6 23. Rxa5 {
White's moves didn't seem particularly difficult, but Black can already resign
with a clear conscience. 1-0 (40) Kamsky,G -Ivanchuk,V Dresden 2008}) ({
In his book, Negi recommended to retreat with the queen immediately.} 8. Qd1 {
It seems to me that there is no need for White to hurry with the kingside
attack.} b6 9. a4 $5 {another typical idea for white in such positions} Ba6 10.
Bb5 Bxb5 11. axb5 Qd7 12. dxc5 $5 (12. Rb1 Qb7 13. Nh3 Nd7 14. Nf4 a6 15. O-O
axb5 16. Rxb5 Qc6 17. Rb1 g6 18. Be3 Kg7 19. Qg4 h5 20. Qg5 Nf5 21. h3 $13 {
1-0 (34) Zherebukh,Y -Xiong,J chess.com INT 2020}) 12... Qxb5 (12... bxc5 13.
Qe2) 13. cxb6 Qxb6 14. Nf3 $14 {[%cal Gc1a3] Negi}) 8... h5 (8... Qa5 9. Bd2
Qa4 10. h5 {will be a transposition to chapter 5}) 9. Qd1 {Now we have a
similar position as the one discussed earlier with the inclusion of h2-h4 and .
..h7-h5. It is truly difficult to say who benefits from this inclusion as
White got the g5-square while Black got one on f5.} b6 10. Bg5 ({Now, at least,
Black should not worry too much about the h5-pawn. You can compare this
position with my game versus Arizmendi mentioned in chapter 2.} 10. Be2 Ba6 11.
Bxh5 cxd4 12. cxd4 Nf5 $132 13. Bg5 $140 Qc7 14. Rh3 Nxd4 $1 {That's how you
shouldn't play as White!}) ({But I can't see anything wrong for white to play} 
10. a4 $5 Ba6 11. Bb5) 10... Qc7 11. Rh3 cxd4 $6 {Black should have tried to
keep the position closed as otherwise the f8-king won't feel safe.} ({I think
it makes more sense to go for} 11... Ba6 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. Ne2 Rc8 14. Rc1 (14.
Nf4 cxd4 15. cxd4 Qxc2) 14... Nf5 15. Nf4 Nb8 16. Nxh5 $140 cxd4 17. cxd4 Nxd4)
({or} 11... Nf5 {and later try and trade the bishops.}) 12. cxd4 Nf5 13. c3 Ba6
14. Bxa6 Nxa6 15. Ne2 Nb8 {Black's play is too slow.} 16. Nf4 g6 17. g4 hxg4
18. Qxg4 Nd7 19. Rc1 Rg8 (19... Rc8 20. h5 gxh5 21. Rxh5 Rg8 22. Rh7 Nxd4 23.
Bh6+ Ke7 24. Ng6+ Ke8 25. cxd4 Qxc1+ 26. Bxc1 Rxc1+ 27. Kd2 $18) 20. h5 gxh5
21. Qxh5 Qc4 {[#]} 22. Ne2 $6 ({White had played excellent chess all the way
up to here and now it was time to strike.} 22. Rf3 $1 {[%cal Gf3f8] and there
is now way for Black to hold this as his pieces all placed chaotically all
over the board and cannot help where this help is needed the most.} Rc8 (22...
Nxe5 23. dxe5 Qe4+ (23... Rxg5 24. Qxg5 Qe4+ 25. Re3 Nxe3 26. fxe3 Qxe3+ 27.
Kd1 Qf3+ 28. Kd2 $18) 24. Kd2 Rxg5 25. Qh8+ Ke7 (25... Rg8 26. Nxe6+ fxe6 27.
Qf6+ Ke8 28. Qxe6+ Ne7 29. Rf7 Qh4 30. Rxe7+ Qxe7 31. Qxg8+ $18) 26. Qf6+ Ke8
27. Nxe6 Qxf3 28. Qxf7+ Kxf7 29. Nxg5+ $18) 23. Nxe6+ fxe6 24. Rxf5+ exf5 25.
e6) ({If White was unwilling to calculate much, he could follow a simple path.
} 22. Kd2 Rc8 23. Rf3 Rc6 24. Ng2 $1 {and Ne3 is coming next. Once again,
Black doesn't have a good defence.} Ke8 25. Ne3 Qa2+ 26. Rc2 Qxa3 27. Rxf5 exf5
28. Nxd5 $18 {[%cal Gd5e7]}) 22... Rc8 23. Rf3 Rc6 24. Ng3 Ke8 25. Nxf5 (25.
Rxf5 exf5 26. Nxf5 Qd3) 25... exf5 26. Rxf5 Rcg6 {Black lost a pawn but at
least he finally managed to coordinate their rooks.} 27. Kd2 Nf8 (27... b5 $5 {
[%cal Gd7b6]}) 28. Be3 Ne6 29. Qe2 {Black's position was still difficult to
handle.} Qa2+ $2 ({It would have been better to go} 29... Qa4 $142 30. c4 $140
Rg1 31. Qh5 Qxa3 32. Qxf7+ Kd8 $132) 30. Rc2 Qb1 31. c4 $1 {Now it's really
over.} Rg4 32. cxd5 Rxd4+ 33. Bxd4 Qxc2+ 34. Kxc2 Nxd4+ 35. Kd3 Nxe2 36. Kxe2
Rg4 37. f4 Rg3 38. Rg5 Rxa3 39. Rg8+ Kd7 40. Rf8 Ke7 41. Rb8 Kd7 42. Rb7+ Ke8
43. d6 {1-0 (43) Anand,V (2758)-Xiong,J (2712) Wijk aan Zee 2020} *

