{Back in 2006, they held a tournament in Amsterdam where the experienced
players competed with the talented youth such as Carlsen, Wang Hao and
Karjakin. In fact, I was Sergey's second during that event. Interestingly,
only Beliavskiy managed to play well among the entire team of Experienced,
while others performed rather badly.} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 c5 5.
a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. a4 {This is not a part of our opening repertoire. 
However, I wanted to show this game anyway to make you better understand the
difference between the positions we would typically get and the positions
where the moves h2-h4-h5 and ...h7-h6 are not included.} ({This would be
similar} 7. Nf3 Bd7 {Threatening Bd7-a4} 8. a4 Qa5 9. Bd2 Nbc6 10. Bb5 f6 {
- and now this is a transposition to our game.}) 7... Nbc6 8. Nf3 Qa5 9. Bd2
Bd7 10. Bb5 f6 $1 {I believe this is the right way for Black to try and create
counterplay[#]} 11. c4 ({Nunn actually had his favorite petline which runs} 11.
Qe2 Qc7 (11... fxe5 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. Qxe5 Bxb5 14. c4 Qd8 15. cxb5 $16 {
1-0 (58) Nunn,J -Brenninkmeijer,J Groningen 1988}) 12. O-O fxe5 {this looks
like a natural improvement for Black} (12... a6 13. Bxc6 Nxc6 14. Bc1 cxd4 15.
exf6 gxf6 16. Nxd4 Qe5 17. Qd2 Rg8 18. Re1 Nxd4 19. cxd4 Qf5 20. Qb4 O-O-O 21.
Ra3 Bc6 22. Rg3 $14 {White's bishop looks much more dangerous than his
counterpart. 1-0 (42) Nunn,J -Hillarp Persson,T Paignton 2000}) 13. Bxc6 Nxc6
14. Nxe5 O-O (14... Nxe5 $6 15. Bf4) 15. Nxc6 Qxc6 $13 {both sides has chances
in this position. In fact, the side who will put his bishop to a better use
will have the advantage.}) 11... Qc7 12. exf6 gxf6 13. cxd5 Nxd5 14. dxc5 O-O-O
15. O-O Rhg8 {Now we have an interesting situation. The position opened up a
lot, which is supposed to benefit the side with the bishop pair. However, here
things are not that simple as the White king isn't particularly comfortable,
either.} 16. a5 e5 17. a6 Nc3 $5 {Back in the day, it was very typical of Wang
Hao to go for complications whenever possible. As you can tell, it used to
work for him well, too!} ({However it could be have been better to continue} 
17... Bg4 $5 18. Be2 $140 Nf4 19. Kh1 Bh5 $36) 18. Bxc3 Bh3 19. axb7+ Kb8 20.
g3 ({It's hard to understand why but the computer thinks that it would have
been better for White to continue} 20. Nh4 Rxd1 21. Rfxd1) 20... Rxd1 21. Rfxd1
Bg4 22. Rd3 Rd8 23. Nd2 Kxb7 24. Ne4 Rxd3 25. cxd3 Bf3 26. Bc4 $2 {Eventually,
the older player couldn't handle this insane tension and went on to collapse
and lose. In fact, the position still wasn't clear despite the fact that White
was a queen down for some minor pieces, though!} (26. Ba6+ Ka8 27. Nd6 Nd8 (
27... Nd4 28. Bxd4 exd4 29. Re1) 28. d4 exd4 29. Bxd4 $13 Ne6 $140 30. Re1 $1)
26... Qd7 $19 {now Qh3 is a huge threat.} 27. Nd2 Bd5 28. Ba6+ Kc7 29. Ne4 Qh3
30. f3 f5 31. Nd2 f4 32. gxf4 exf4 33. Rf1 Qf5 34. Kg2 h5 35. Rb1 Ne5 36. Ne4
Qg6+ 37. Kf2 Ng4+ 38. fxg4 Qxa6 39. Nf6 Qxd3 40. Be5+ Kc6 0-1

